{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"91f239f9-13d5-4f08-9109-0edd99a5949f","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is exactly what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — **Reinstalls** the same versions already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but won't pull newer versions needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK changed → versions are mismatched → `update`. If workloads were the right version but files were missing/corrupt → `repair`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf issues persist after updating, also verify your installed workloads with `dotnet workload list`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e6c5cdfc-bf64-4cb1-9443-c8d417cef0bf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to look at any files or run any commands.","outputTokens":259,"requestId":"B7D4:36941C:1257CA:17E317:69FFD72D"},"id":"443524e4-c2b3-4a79-8d45-b4ee35e43dc6","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:54:14.826Z","parentId":"ddfd6abd-75c3-46c7-a631-556adb11a5d1"}
